column3: Quality of Experience
column4: This  KXI is a calculated value based on all of the other KPIs that indicates overall quality of experience (Service and Network) of the chosen context

column3: Customer Experience Index
column4: This KXI is a calculated value based on the combination of the QOE with other customer attributes such as Billing, Complaints and Service Centre Contact.  It is updated daily.

column3: Audio MOS Down (#)
column4: This KPI indicates the Average Audio MOS Downlink on a range of 1-5.   It is a measure of voice quality which is used as a way to assess the human users opinion of call quality. The score reports on three different factors: Listening Quality, Transmission Quality, Conversational Quality.  5 is representing the highest customer experience.

column3: Throughput DL (mbps)
column4: This KPI indicates  average HTTP download throughput per user.   High throughput can cause a capacity problem and low throughput can indicate a latency problem and degrading customer experience.

column3: Throughput UL (mbps)
column4: This KPI indicates  average HTTP upload throughput per user.  Low throughput can cause a capacity problem and low throughput can indicate a latency problem and degrading customer experience.

column3: Jitter DL (ms)
column4: This KPI indicates the variation of time taken to download data packets.  The higher the variation, the lower the customer experience impacts.

column3: Jitter UL (ms)
column4: This KPI indicates the variation of time taken to upload data packets.  The higher the variation, the lower the customer experience impacts.

column3: Stall count (#)
column4: This KPI measures the average number of stalls which occurred during the video playout. The value in this KPI is for the period in which the data source generates the report (For e.g. reports generated every 15 mins). The sum total of all stalls at the end of the video stream duration gives the overall stall count.

column3: Stall Time (s)
Video MOS DL (#)
column4: This KPI indicates the Average Video MOS Downlink on a range of 1-5.   It is a measure of voice quality which is used as a way to assess the human users opinion of video quality. The score reports on three different factors: Listening Quality, Transmission Quality, Viewing Quality.  5 is representing the highest customer experience.

column3: CS Dropped Calls (%)
column4: This KPI measures the percentage of calls that dropped during the connection (eg dropped)

column3: CS Attachment Failure Rate (%)
column4: This KPI is the percentage attach success rate for calls across the network.  This usually indicates network coverage and lower customer experience issues if low.

column3: CS GPS Failure Rate (%)
column4: This KPI is the percentage of gps update events that failed (gps coverage)

column3: CS MOS (#)
column4: This KPI indicates the Average Circuit Switch MOS on a range of 1-5.   It is a measure of customer opinion, with 5 representing the highest customer experience.

column3: Video Stall Time Rate (%)
column4: Percentage of time for which the video stalled of the total stream duration

column3: Data Packet Loss Rate (%)
column4: This KPI indicates the packet loss rate which is a measure of the link integrity and is defined as the fraction of the total transmitted packets that did not arrive at the receiver.

column3: Data Packet Retransmission Rate DL (%)
column4: This KPI refers to the rate of retransmitted packets as observed on the core network for TCP or UDP connection during the download of content from the external PDN.

column3: Data Packet Retransmission Rate UL (%)
column4: This KPI refers to the rate of retransmitted packets as observed on the core network for a TCP or UDP connection during the upload of content from the external PDN

column3: vOLTE Dropped Calls (%)
column4: This KPI measures the percentage of calls that dropped during the connection (eg dropped)

column3: voLTE MOS (#)
column4: This KPI indicates the Average VOLTE MOS on a range of 1-5.   It is a measure of customer opinion, with 5 representing the highest customer experience.

column3: PS Handover Delay (ms)
column4: This KPI indicates delay experienced when handing over between technologies or cells.

column3: PS Handover Success Rate (%)
column4: This KPI indicates the percentage of handover requests that were successful.  Handover requests are when a subscriber moves around the network and changes from cell to technology

column3: Routing Area Update Delay (s)
column4: When roaming, this KPI indicates is the delay in updates to routing areas

column3: Routing Area Update Success Rate (%)
column4: When roaming, this KPI represents the percentage of successful routing access updates

column3: Tracking Area Update Delay (s)
column4: When roaming, this is the delay in updates to Tracking Area

column3: Tracking Area Update Success Rate (%)
column4: When roaming, this is the percentage of successful tracking access updates

column3: PS Attachnent Delay (ms)
column4: This KPI is the average time taken for a call to be connected to the packet switch network.  The higher the time taken, the lower the customer experience.

column3: PS Attachment Success Rate (%)
column4: This KPI is the percentage attach success rate for calls across the packet switch network.  This usually indicates network coverage and lower customer experience issues if low.

column3: PS Initial Context Setup Delay (ms)
column4: This KPI indicates the delay experienced when initially setting up context on network connection (like obtaining IP address)

column3: PS Initial Context Setup Success Rate (%)
column4: This KPI indicates the success rate of setting up context on network connection (like obtaining IP address)

column3: Pdp Context Activation Delay
column4: This KPI indicates the delay experienced when initially setting up context on network connection (like obtaining IP address)

column3: Pdp Context Activation SuccessRate
column4: This KPI indicates the success rate of setting up context on network connection (like obtaining IP address)

column3: Dedicated Bearer Context Activation Delay (ms)
column4: Delay experienced when initially setting up context on network connection (like obtaining IP address)

column3: Dedicated Bearer Context Activation Success Rate (%)
column4: Percentage of context setup requests that were successful

column3: Default Bearer Context Activation Delay (ms)
column4: Delay experienced when initially setting up context on network connection (like obtaining IP address)

column3: Default Bearer Context Activation Success Rate (%)
column4: Percentage of context setup requests that were successful

column3: VOLTE Service Reqeust Delay (ms)
column4: Data request delay in Volte network

column3: VOLTE Service Request Success Rate (%)
column4: Data request success rate in Volte network

column3: Application Response Time (s)
column4: This KPI indicates the speed of access to a webpage/application accessed.  It is the delay from the moment the user requests the service and the moment the user sees the first web page content.  The lower the value the better the customer experience. HTTP access time, or the delay from the moment the user requests the desired web page and the moment the user sees the first web page content.

column3: Time to Start (s)
column4: This KPI measures the average time of the server response to a playback request from the client i.e. the time taken for a video to start playing post the user initiation or in case of a auto play video then it is the time taken for the video to start.

column3: CS Call Connect Delay (ms)
column4: This KPI is the average time taken for a call to be connected to the dialled number.  The higher the time taken, the lower the customer experience.

column3: CS Blocked Calls (%)
column4: This KPI measures the percentage of calls that failed to be setup (eg blocked)

column3: Web (HTTP) Response Fail Rate (%)
column4: This KPI indicates  the availability of a webpage or application accessed by a subscriber.

column3: voLTE Blocked Calls (%)
column4: This KPI indicates the number of calls blocked before the connected to the dialled number

column3: voLTE Connection Delay (ms)
column4: This KPI indicates the delay experience before a call is connected to the dialled number.

column3: voLte Registration Fail (%)
column4: This KPI represents the percentage of failed registrations on volte

column3: voLte Srvcc Fail (%)
column4: This KPI represents the percentage of SRVCC requests that failed.

column3: Data Volume Download (mb)
column4: This KPI refers to total number of transmitted  packets as observed on the core network for TCP or UDP connection during the download of content from the external PDN

column3: Data Volume Upload (mb)
column4: This KPI refers to total number of transmitted packets as observed on the core network for a TCP or UDP connection during the upload of content from the external PDN
